                        <h2>Understanding Stress</h2>
                        <p>Stress is a natural reaction to lifeâ€™s challenges. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including work, relationships, and financial pressures. While some stress can be motivating, excessive stress can lead to serious health issues.</p>

                        <h3>Types of Stress</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Acute Stress:</strong> Short-term stress that can be exciting in small doses but exhausting when experienced frequently.</li>
                            <li><strong>Chronic Stress:</strong> Long-term stress that can lead to serious health problems, such as anxiety and depression.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Signs of Stress</h3>
                        <p>Common signs of stress include:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Headaches</li>
                            <li>Fatigue</li>
                            <li>Sleep disturbances</li>
                            <li>Irritability</li>
                            <li>Difficulty concentrating</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Managing Stress Effectively</h3>
                        <p>Here are some techniques to manage stress:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Practice mindfulness and meditation.</li>
                            <li>Engage in regular exercise.</li>
                            <li>Establish a healthy work-life balance.</li>
                            <li>Talk to someone you trust about your feelings.</li>
                            <li>Consider professional help if needed.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Resources for Support</h3>
                        <p>If you need help managing stress, consider reaching out to:</p>
